<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Little Headway Made in Second Day Indo-Pak Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Little headway was made when
the Indo-Pak foreign secretary-level talks entered its second day
here today as both sides stuck to their own stand on the Kashmir
issue.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the end of the three round of talks at
the Hyderabad House here, a senior Pakistan official said that
many substantive issues were discussed. The pace was as expected,
neither slow nor too fast.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan toughened its stand on Jammu and Kashmir, insisting
that some progress should be made on Kashmir before other
outstanding issues could be tackled.
</P>
<P>
Indian Foreign Secretary Salman Haider made it clear in the
talks that New Delhi was not prepared to consider anything that
would disturb the country's secular unity and jeopardize its
sovereignty, informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Islamabad would under no circumstance agree to any proposal to
keep the Kashmir issue outside the agenda of the four-day talks, a
Pakistan official said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, which got bogged down on the agenda today, would
resume their talks tomorrow.  
</P>
</TEXT>
