<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Needed for Common Prosperity in Asia: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Asia's future depends on Asian countries, Stephen Leong,
assistant director-general of Malaysia's Institute of Strategic
and International Studies (ISIS), said in an exclusive interview
with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
And he challenged Asian countries to prove to the world that
in spite of their differences, they could work together.
</P>
<P>
"Let us prove to them (western experts on Asia), let us prove
to ourselves that we can work together for common prosperity," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Everyone wants to see long-lasting peace in the region. That
means "not just peace without conflict but peace that is related
to what I would call productive peace and productive peace is
development peace," Leong said.
</P>
<P>
He said Asian countries have a long way to go to become
developed countries and to do so they need peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Leong said the goal of seeing a united Southeast Asia was
slowly being realized through the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
As for China's role in the region, he said China's size meant
that any of its actions would have an impact on the region, as
well as the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Leong spoke highly of the reform and opening policy which China
adopted in 1978 and said he was optimistic about stability in China
following Deng Xiaoping's death.
</P>
<P>
On China's resumption of sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1,
Leong said this was a "major achievement" for China. He believed
the Chinese government would ensure Hong Kong remained a thriving
economic and financial center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
