<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues Regulation to Protect New Plant Strains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Signed by Premier Li Peng, a
Regulation on the Protection of New Plant Strains, which was
released today, will go into effect on October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The regulation is aimed at encouraging the cultivation and use
of new plant strains, boosting the development of agriculture and
forestry, and protecting the strain developers' rights, the
regulation says.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulation, new plant strains refer to plants
cultivated artificially or developed from wild plants, which hold
new and stable properties.
</P>
<P>
The 46-article regulation states that relevant agricultural and
forestry departments under the State Council are held responsible
for examining and approving new strains, and individuals and work
units developing the strains have exclusive rights to them, which
can be sold to others.
</P>
<P>
The regulation has detailed articles on qualifications for
approving new plant strains, new strain application procedures,
the examination and final approval of new strain rights, and the
protection duration of new strains.
</P>
<P>
Those who make illegal profits from new strains developed by
others will be entitled to penalties, according to the
regulation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
