<HEADLINE> Pakistan Closes Border to Stem Wheat Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has sealed all its
frontiers to stem the cross-border smuggling of wheat, Agriculture
Minister Abida Hussain said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistan government ordered the closure of borders on
Thursday last, Abida Hussain said during a press conference.
</P>
<P>
She said the Punjab government also had shut down some of the
flour mills in Punjab, which were found guilty of hoarding wheat,
and had confiscated some trucks involved in the smuggling.
</P>
<P>
These measures were taken to overcome the prevailing wheat
crisis, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Giving a detailed background of the present crisis, Abida
Hussain said that in September and October last year about 597,000
tons of wheat was released to the flour mills in excess of the
quantity released in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
This excess release caused a shortfall of wheat for 25 days,
which was never met, she said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the minister said wheat consignments from abroad were
also delayed by ten days, aggravating the crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, she said the situation during the last 48 hours had
eased with the off-loading of wheat at Port Qasim and its
transportation to up-country.
</P>
<P>
The minister, however, said the larger ships were not booked
for wheat supply which involved misappropriation of about 10
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
She said wheat worth 500 million dollars was imported last
year.
</P>
<P>
She said the support price of wheat in the bordering countries
was two to four times more than that of Pakistan, resulting in the
smuggling of wheat to the neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
The pricing structure of wheat crop was faulty and it needed to
be rectified, said Abida Hussain.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, she feared a shortfall of 10,000 tons in
wheat supply next year.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan had to bear the food burden of Afghan refugees and the
donor countries had minimized their support following the
withdrawal of Soviet forces.  
</P>
</TEXT>
