<HEADLINE> Accord Could Offset NATO Expansion Effects: Primakov </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 29 (Xinhua) -- The planned charter defining
relations between Russia and NATO could offset the negative
effects of NATO's eastward expansion, Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said today after talks with German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
Although he repeated Moscow's opposition to NATO expansion,
Primakov said, "If we succeed in signing a document with NATO
(North Atlantic Treaty Organization), we will be able to
neutralize possible negative consequences which could emerge from
its expansion."
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton
agreed at their summit in Helsinki last week to sign a charter to
define Russian-NATO relations.
</P>
<P>
Echoing a similar remark by Russian President Boris Yeltsin at
the summit, Primakov said Moscow still regarded NATO expansion as
"a mistake and perhaps the biggest mistake since the end of the
Cold War."
</P>
<P>
But he said Russia was ready to work to ensure that Cold
War-style divisions in Europe remained a thing of the past.
There should be no "new dividing lines" in Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel told reporters that he hoped the document on
NATO-Russian ties, whether a charter or not, could be agreed at a
meeting of NATO foreign ministers in Portugal in May, before the
alliance's Madrid summit in July when it is due to choose the
first wave of new members from former Warsaw Pact countries.
</P>
<P>
Primakov warned though that the document was far from ready and
that there were still thorny issues to be negotiated between NATO
and Russia, such as the deployment of NATO conventional forces and
military infrastructure on the territory of new members.
</P>
<P>
Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic are widely expected to
be the first east European countries to win NATO membership.
</P>
</TEXT>
