<HEADLINE> Arafat Slams Israel for Escalating Current </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today blasted Israel for escalating
the current tension by imposing conditions on resuming peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who returned from Cairo, Egypt, told reporters that
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's "orders and
decisions" were the causes of the current tension. He rejected
Netanyahu's demand that he launch a sustained crackdown on
terrorism rather than only making verbal pledges before resuming
the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that only Israel's "honest and accurate
implementation" of the signed peace accords could get the peace
process moving again.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on his meeting in Rabat of Morocco Thursday with
U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross, Arafat said the
U.S. was also "against the violence of settlement and the
Judaization of Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Ross returned home from here late Friday after holding two
meetings with Netanyahu. Ross reportedly put forward new ideas
on resuming the stalled Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, but no
detail has been released. The U.S. State Department described
Ross' talks with Israeli and Palestinian leaders as
constructive, while acknowledging that much more work needed to
be done to resume the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is to convene the PNA cabinet meeting tonight to brief
the results of his meeting with Ross and the meeting of the
Jerusalem Committee which he attended last week in Rabat. Arab
leaders attending the meeting adopted a resolution calling on
Arab countries to reconsider their ties with Israel to protest
Israel's settlement policies in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry suspected that the relatively
moderate resolution contained secret clauses aimed at sabotaging
the normalization of ties between Israel and Arab
countries. Eitan Bentsur, director-general of the ministry, also
called on the upcoming meeting of Arab foreign ministers to end
the tension and verbal attacks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, clashes between Israeli soldiers and Palestinian
protesters continued for the ninth day on the West Bank. At
least five Palestinians were wounded by rubber bullets fired by
Israeli soldiers guarding the Jewish holy site of Rachel's Tomb
near the West Bank city of Bethlehem. In southern Ramallah,
north of Jerusalem, dozens of Palestinian youth also threw stones
at Israeli border policemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
