<HEADLINE> Cambodia Heralds Film Revival with International Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 29 (Xinhua) -- The first Southeast Asian
Biennial Film Festival opened today at the new Inter-Continental
Hotel, marking another step in war-scarred Cambodia's return to
the world stage.
</P>
<P>
Billed as the largest international event Cambodia has hosted
in nearly 30 years, the week-long festival has attracted more than
70 Asian and French movie stars and filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
During the festival, 12 recent films from Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam will
compete for awards given by an international jury.
</P>
<P>
However, no Cambodian films are entered in the jury competition
partly because of the destruction of the once-thriving local
motion picture industry, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Before 1970, Cambodia had a prosperous film industry with more
than 43 cinemas in the capital and a host of prolific filmmakers
including then-Prince, now King, Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
But the film industry was devastated in the following two
decades of civil war when cinemas were destroyed, old movies
lost and many film makers killed.
</P>
<P>
The organizers hope the festival will help the revival of
the Cambodian film industry.
</P>
<P>
The festival offers an opportunity for Southeast Asian
nations to understand each other's cultures and for the film
professionals to exchange viewpoints and improve film-making
skills, they say.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a "Fringe Festival" will be held to present 33
films that are not taking part in the competition, including two
produced by China and a dozen by Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Other events during the festival include a "Retrospective" of
French actor Alain Delon, debates and lectures and a photo
exhibition presenting the work of Southeast Asian photographers.
</P>
<P>
The festival is sponsored by the Cambodian Ministry of Culture
and Fine Arts, the Embassies of Southeast Asian countries in Phnom
Penh and the French Embassy in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
A grand official opening of the festival will be held Sunday at
Chaktomuk Hall attended by Queen Norodom Monineath who returned
from Beijing Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
