<HEADLINE> Russian President Meets with CIS Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
met separately today with several leaders of former Soviet
Union countries in an effort to ease tension and enhance economic
cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
The series of meetings followed Friday's one-day summit of the
12-nation Commonwealth of Independent States(CIS), which Yeltsin
was elected head of for the fourth time .
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma,
Yeltsin promised to visit Ukraine in late May or early June to
advance talks on the ownership of the disputed former Black Sea
Fleet.
</P>
<P>
He had previously refused to go to Kiev to sign a comprehensive
friendship treaty until the row is resolved.
</P>
<P>
"I will visit Ukraine no matter whether the treaty is signed or
not," the ITAR-Tass news agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also met with the presidents of Armenia and Azerbaijan,
Levon Ter-Petrosian and Geidar Aliev and said Russia would do its
best to help the two countries solve their nine-year conflict over
the disputed enclave of Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
He also told Georgian President Eduard SHevardnadze that Russia
will play an active role in settling the current conflict in the
Georgian separatist province of Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president spoke with Kyrgyzstan President Askar
Akayev on deepening bilateral economic ties and said he was
pleased that the country plans to make Russian its official
language.
</P>
<P>
Friday's CIS summit was originally set for January, but was
postponed due to Yeltsin's health problems. The next summit is
expected to be held in June this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
