<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Foreign Ministers Hold Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Friendship and cooperation are
the keystone of Sino-Japanese relationship, which should not be
affected by the existing problems in bilateral ties, Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen told his Japanese counterpart Ikeda Yukihiko
here today.
</P>
<P>
During a two and half hour talks between the two foreign
ministers at the Diaoyutai State Guest House, Qian said that as
the world polarizes at a growing pace, the growth of the friendly,
neighborly, cooperative, and mutually beneficial relations between
China and Japan is of great importance to both countries, Asia,
and the world.
</P>
<P>
Noting that since the resumption of diplomatic ties between the
two countries, friendship and cooperation have been the keystone
of bilateral relations, with remarkable achievements in political
dialogue, economic cooperation and people-to-people exchanges, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the hard-won growth of Sino-Japanese
relationship is the result of the painstaking efforts of several
generations of both countries and should be treasured by the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
Though the bilateral relations still have some noticeable
problems, he said, the two sides should proceed from the overall
situation and have the farsight to handle and resolve these
problems properly, so as not to let them to affect the normal
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the principles of the Sino-Japanese joint
declaration and the treaty of peace and friendship between the two
countries are the political basis of the growth of Sino-Japanese
ties and the criteria for proper resolution of existing problems
and differences between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two countries should, in the first place,
have a clear awareness of this point and lead the two peoples to
work for the development of Sino-Japanese friendship, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed appreciation for the positive posture that
Japanese Prime Minister Hashimoto Ryutaro and Ikeda have made on
this issue since the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that Ikeda visited China as foreign
minister. It was also a contact between high-ranking officials of
the two countries in the year that marks the 25th anniversary of
the normalization of the relations between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Qian wishes that Ikeda's visit will achieve positive results
and advance the healthy, stable development of bilateral
relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
