<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1700 GMT March 29 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Little headway was made when the Indo-Pak foreign
secretary-level talks entered its second day here Saturday as both
sides stuck to their own stand on the Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- Albania's ruling Democratic Party on Saturday
officially called for an investigation into former defense
minister Safet Zhulali, who fled the country amid the anarchy now
gripping the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A Palestinian minister on Saturday urged Arab foreign
ministers to send a strong message to Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu at the upcoming Arab League Council meeting as
the recent U.S. mediation has turned out to be no avail.
</P>
<P>
Lagos -- A dust-to-dawn curfew has been imposed on the oil city
of Warri and its environs in Delta State, south Nigeria, to curb
the week-long crisis from escalating.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia and Uzbekistan signed a border cooperation
treaty Friday, the Russian Directorate of Border Guard Troops
announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Under the treaty, signed by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
Uzbek President Islam Karimov, the two countries will cooperate in
defending their borders, exchanging information, countering
terrorism, weapons and drug smuggling and illegal border
crossings.
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- The Zairean government and the rebels will begin
talks in South Africa early next week, a report reaching here said
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an unidentified S. African government
official as saying "senior Foreign Ministry officials began
preparations today (Friday) to host peace talks in South Africa"
which were likely to take place on Monday or Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
