<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Heroin Traffickers Sentenced to Death in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Two Hong Kong men who tried to
transport 18.1 kilogram of heroin to the Netherlands via Ho Chi
Minh City were sentenced to death in Vietnam on Friday, today's
Vietnam News quoted a court official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The two, 34-years-old Sun Chi Kin and 24-years-old Chan
Chun Hung Sammy, holding British passports, were arrested in
March last year after customs officers seized the drug hidden in
their two suitcases upon their arrival at Ho Chi Minh city's
international airport from Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
They held fake Portuguese passports under false names when they
were arrested.
</P>
<P>
The amount of heroin carried by the two Hong Kong men was
reportedly the biggest haul yet in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
They have 15 days to lodge an appeal against the sentence
before going a firing squad, said court officials in
Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
In Vietnam, one is subject to death penalty to possess or
transport more than one kilogram of heroin.
</P>
<P>
Up to now four foreigners have received death sentences for
drug-related crimes in Vietnam including a Hong Kong man who was
executed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Vietnam discovered more than 3,800 cases of drug
trafficking and arrested 6,650 people for drug-related offenses.
</P>
<P>
However, official sources here said drug trafficking and abuse in
Vietnam is still on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that Vietnam is both a growing market and a transit
route for narcotics from the notorious Golden Triangle opium-poppy
growing area, which straddles the borders of Laos, Burma and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Young people seem to be the most susceptible to drug addiction. The
arrest of four heroin dealers and 94 young drug users earlier this month
in Ho Chi Minh City shocked the country.
</P>
<P>
A report made by the anti-narcotics program of the national committee
for ethnic minorities and the highlands said that there are about 140,000
drug addicts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
To deal with the problem, an all-out anti-drug campaign as of March 13
was waged by the Communist Youth League, the Women's Union and the
Environment Bureau in Ho Chi Minh City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
