<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization of Zambian Copper Conglomerate Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 29 (Xinhua) -- The pace of privatizing the
state-owned copper conglomerate, Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) will not be slackened because the value of the mines could
slump if the process was slowed down.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by Zambian Finance Minister Ronald Penza in
an interview with local press here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It is like selling a second-hand car with a knock engine and
you delay so much that in the end all the buyers realize that
your car is finished," Penza was quoted by "Times of Zambia" as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"We have 39 bidders for the ZCCM. This is very encouraging. We
shall handle the sale of the ZCCM diligently and efficiently
because delaying may mean having nothing to sell in the end," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Penza added that it is not a question of how much the ZCCM
will be sold for but what the benefits of privatizing the
conglomerate will be to the nation.
</P>
<P>
ZCCM is the major support of the country's economy by earning
about 80 percent of the country's foreign exchange. In July last
year, the government publicized the program for its
privatization. The Zambia privatization agency opened bids for
the sale of a number of mines and assets on February 28 this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
