<HEADLINE> UK's Labor Party Urges IRA to Call Truce to Enter Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, the political wing of
the Irish Republican Army (IRA), could enter multi-party talks
under a Labor government this summer if the IRA calls a cease-fire
now, the UK's opposition Labor Party said today.
</P>
<P>
Labor's Northern Ireland spokeswoman Mo Mowlam urged Sinn Fein
to show commitment to peace by words and deeds.
</P>
<P>
She told BBC, "If they show by word and deed that they are
committed to the democratic process, then we think they ought to
safely move into the talks process."
</P>
<P>
She added that if the IRA called an immediate truce during
April and May, entry to talks, which will resume on June 3, was "a
high possibility."
</P>
<P>
Britain is due to hold its general election on May 1, and the
Labor Party, which leads the ruling Conservative Party by more
than 20 percentage points in opinion polls, could resume
responsibility for troubled Northern Ireland if it wins the
election.
</P>
<P>
Mowlam made the statement one day after the IRA claimed
responsibility Friday for Wednesday's two bomb attacks on railway
lines in Wilmslow in northwestern England, which severely
disrupted railway services but caused no injuries.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein welcomed Mowlam's remarks and described her comments
as "very encouraging," but gave no hint of the possibility of a
new IRA truce.
</P>
<P>
Pat Doherty, vice-president of Sinn Fein, told the BBC that the
British government must set a date for Sinn Fein's entry into
peace talks and must drop all preconditions for the talks before
they could call a new truce.
</P>
<P>
The IRA, fighting British rule in Northern Ireland, has carried
out a series of bomb attacks on mainland Britain since February
1996 when it ended a 17-month cease-fire in protest against the
lack of progress in talks aimed at bringing about peace in the
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
