<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-29 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Urges Israel to Honor Commitments to Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today called upon Israel to shelve its "arrogant" policy and
fulfill its commitments to the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the sixth annual conference of the National
Democratic Party Economic Committee, Mubarak said Israel had to
"understand the nature of the region and drop its arrogance."
</P>
<P>
"There should be sincere desire, flexibility and understanding
on the part of each party of the attitudes of all parties," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin was keen to initiate
movement on the Syrian-Israeli and Lebanese-Israeli tracks side by
side with the Palestinian-Israeli track, he said.
</P>
<P>
"There was an undeclared Israeli readiness from Rabin to
restore the Golan in return for normal relations and negotiations
between Israel and Syria, (which) had reached the point of
discussing details of security arrangements," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
However, reviewing the recent peace developments, the president
said Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu is "using an
language of haughtiness and imagining that (other) peoples can be
taught, which is totally unacceptable to the Arabs."
</P>
<P>
He urged Netanyahu to "address Arab society, with which he
lives, in its language and in accordance with its traditions and
to respect its culture."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader said he had warned at various meetings with
the Israeli premier that the issue of Jerusalem is sensitive
because it is related to religions and should be approached with
caution.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has denounced the Israeli decision on building a
6,500-unit Jewish neighborhood in Arab East Jerusalem, saying it
has led to an impasse and provoked Palestinian riots that
continued for the ninth day in the West Bank and culminated in
last week's suicide bombing attack in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Some Muslim countries, including Egypt, have threatened to
sever ties with the Jewish state as things have deteriorated since
late last month.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, Egypt is keen on the realization of
stability and peace for the people of the region, but Israel has
failed to make good on its commitment to the peace accords with
the Palestinians as well the 1979 peace treaty with Egypt, the
first between Israel and an Arab country.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt honors its agreements and pledges and in the meantime
calls on the other party to fulfill its obligations and implement
its agreements as regards the Palestinian issue which is the core
of the Mideast conflict," Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt intervenes among the parties when her assistance is
requested, but it does not negotiate on behalf of the Palestinians,
who are their own decision-makers and who are responsible for the
fate of their own people, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak went to Washington early this month in a line of
several Middle East leaders to seek much-needed U.S. backing for
the peace promotion in the region as the peace process fell in
what he termed "its worst crisis since the 1970s."
</P>
<P>
Egypt, together with other Arab countries, this month sponsored
a U.N. General Assembly resolution that condemns Israel's
settlement activities in occupied Arab lands. It said the
U.S. double veto of a similar move in the U.N. Security Council
has encouraged Israel to proceed in a wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the current relations between the two countries,
Mubarak said "Egypt and Israel maintain normal relations and Egypt
plays an effective role and gives advice."
</P>
<P>
Egypt advised against peace and stability for "only one party,"
he said, adding that the realization of Middle East peace requires
strong faith in the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
"It should be made clear that negotiations on the Palestinian
and Syrian tacks be based on restoration of land to their owners
as was the case of Egyptian lands," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1979 peace treaty, Israel returned the Sinai
peninsula to Egypt in April 1982 after 26 years of occupation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
