<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Workers' Unrest Embarrasses EU Ambition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- European workers have been
taking to the streets lately in protest against job losses,
spending cuts and increasing financial and social insecurity, but
most of them are unaware that by doing so, they were embarrassing
the ambitious European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
In order to meet the criteria set up in the Treaty of
Maastricht for a single currency membership, the governments of
most European countries are trying their best to slash social
benefits and public spending for reductions of their annual budget
deficits.
</P>
<P>
However, here came the protests at such a seemingly crucial
moment. The most conspicuous one might be the cross-border strikes
by Renault workers, who have been angered by plant closures by the
French automobile company in Belgium, Spain and France and the
ensuing job losses.
</P>
<P>
German coal miners worried about vanishing subsidies and French
medical interns upset by budget cutbacks also took to the streets.
And a total of 300,000 Italian workers demonstrated to demand that
the government create more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Another trouble is that there will be other calendars,
including the French and German elections calendars, to go
together with the EU's preparations for its most ambitious dream
-- economic and monetary union (EMU) by January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
But the essential message from the workers' unrest is that in a
paradise of welfare systems, you have to be extremely careful with
any kind of reform or change which might negatively influence the
job holders who have been protected by welfare for decades.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts say that the monetary union and the present mass
unemployment in Europe should not necessarily be connected with
each other. It is just unlucky for the EU to have trouble with
employment when it is struggling for the EMU, they say.
</P>
<P>
"That is most unfortunate because it is so easy to blame the
(Maastricht) treaty when it is really the structural reforms that
need to be tackled," said a Europe-watcher called Mr. Horne.
</P>
<P>
However, the economists still think that the Maastricht single
currency process should be blamed at least for the budget cutbacks
by the governments of EU member countries, which are slowing down
overall economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the contradicting thoughts regarding the connection
between European workers' strikes and the EMU, some other analysts
have reached the conclusion that Europe needs to undertake
structural reforms, but the EMU process and new restrictions on
public expenditure at a time of low growth are worsening the
problem.
</P>
<P>
The European workers seem to forget to blame another main cause
of their problem -- economic globalization, which has compelled
many European companies to transfer their manufacturing operations
from EU countries to Eastern Europe or Asia, where cheaper labor
can be easily found.
</P>
<P>
Another worrying factor which needs to be mentioned is that the
governments of some EU countries are continuing to coddle their
welfare-dependent citizens by giving in to the demands raised by
the striking workers.
</P>
<P>
But the EMU process, which has become in a way a scapegoat for
the prevalent unemployment in Western Europe, is in no way a good
solution to the workers' unsatisfaction, which some policymakers
in Europe are worried that some day could turn into more serious
forms of social unrest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
