<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Reforms Urged in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 29 (Xinhua) -- African countries were today
urged to continue with their economic and financial reforms, with
a view to achieving sustainable development for their economies
and for their effective integration in the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in a draft resolution "Growth and
Development Finance in Africa and Financial Sector Reforms"
prepared by a five-day experts meeting which closed here today,
for adoption by the forthcoming sixth session of the Conference
of African Ministers of Finance which will be held here from
March 31 to April 2, this year.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution welcomed the steps taken by a number of
African countries to improve the efficiency of their money and
capital markets and to create new ones where they do not exist.
</P>
<P>
It called upon African countries to implement appropriate
policies to reduce gradually their heavy dependency on external
financing and to improve mobilization of domestic savings and
non-debt creating flows.
</P>
<P>
It also appealed to the international community to step up
significantly their financial support to African countries in the
implementation of their economic and financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
In another draft resolution "the Debt Problem and Its Impact
on Africa's Development Process", the experts meeting appealed to
the multilateral financial institutions and international
community to continue to support African countries with
concessional financing necessary for them to develop and
rehabilitate their social sectors, especially education and
health, and improve and maintain their infrastructures. It called
upon African countries in collaboration with the international
community and multilateral institutions to intensify their
efforts to find a durable solution to the debt problem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the meeting also prepared a draft declaration "on
Growth and Development Finance in Africa at the Turn of the
Century, Financial Sector Reforms and the African Debt Problem"
proposed for adoption by the sixth session of the conference of
African Ministers of Finance.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the ministries of finance and central banks
from African countries, as well as delegates from international
organizations and united nations bodies attended the meeting. The
meeting discussed financial reforms in Africa, exchange rate
management, development of capital markets and the African debt
problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
