<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scottish Tory Chairman Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Britain's ruling
Conservative Party in Scotland Michael Hirst resigned today over
what he described as a "past indiscretion" in his private life,
dealing another heavy blow on the Tories.
</P>
<P>
Hirst wrote to Prime Minister John Major saying that he was
resigning rather than embarrass the party.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Major has accepted his resignation.
</P>
<P>
Hirst said in the letter, "I very deeply regret these
circumstances which have caused great distress to my family and
which may, I fear, cause embarrassment to the party in the current
climate."
</P>
<P>
He was the third high-ranking Conservative to resign in a week
over sexual and money scandals which dogged the party which,
facing a general election on May 1, is more than 20 percentage
points behind the opposition Labor Party in national opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
However, Annabel Goldie, who has taken the place of Hirst as
the party's chairman in Scotland, dismissed suggestions that the
incident would worsen the Conservatives' election chances.
</P>
<P>
She said, "I think the public is beginning to feel it has had
enough, that it is beginning to resent the attempt by the media to
judge... to devastate and destroy the lives of people who in many
respects are good, upright and honorable people who have merely
done what many others have done -- made a mistake."
</P>
<P>
She added that voters are more concerned with the issues, such
as the economy, health and education, that affect them, than with
personal morality. 
</P>
