<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Telephone Company to Cut Jobs for Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian telephone company
Belgacom has said recently that it would cut 6,500 jobs to slash
costs in preparation for the scheduled opening up of the European
Union's telecommunications market next year.
</P>
<P>
Belgacom, which employs some 26,000 people, said the unemployed
workers would be offered early retirement and another 6,000 would
be redeployed to try to "get prepared for increasing competition."
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said Belgacom was not forcing anyone to take early
retirement and it was impossible to say how much the program would
cost until the number of those accepting early retirement was
known. The program will run until December 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said that a one-time payment equivalent to six months'
salary, a monthly allowance equal to 75 percent of their monthly
salary till age 60 and a full pension after that would be offered
to the employees who were born before July 1, 1947 and had been
working for the company for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Belgacom is 49.5 percent-owned by Ameritech Corp., Singapore
Telecommunications Ltd. and Tele Danmark AS, with the rest held by
the state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
