<HEADLINE> ECOMOG to Boost Security at Liberia's Borders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- The high command of the West
African peacekeeping force, known as ECOMOG, has reiterated the
force's determination to continuously enhance security at the
Liberian borders.
</P>
<P>
This is to boost confidence of returning refugees and
safeguard Liberia from any influx of arms, Brigadier-General Joe
Kwateng, deputy commander of ECOMOG, said in Tabou, a
southwestern town in Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
According to the News Agency of Nigeria today, the ECOMOG
officer was in the town on Wednesday representing ECOMOG Force
Commander Major-General Victor Malu at the presentation of six
patrol crafts by the United States government to Abidjan for
coastal border patrols.
</P>
<P>
Kwateng was quoted as saying that the security of the Liberian
borders was paramount to ECOMOG as one of the essential tasks
necessary for the achievement of lasting peace and encouraging
Liberian refugees to return home.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) has
re-launched its comprehensive voluntary reintegration program for
Liberia's estimated 768,000 refugees residing in neighboring West
African countries.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of the refugees, following improvement in
security in Liberia, is expected to begin from April and will
last for about 18 months, the UNHCR said. 
</P>
