<HEADLINE> Germany to Seek Better Coordination in Repatriating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 29 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
said today that he and European Union commissioner Hans van den
Broek will visit Bosnia recently to seek a better coordination in
the repatriation of Bosnian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation can only be carried out in a standardized and
coordinative manner based on full data about the refugees,
including their places of origin and ethnic identities, Kinkel
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Defending a decision by interior ministers from Germany's 16
federal states to carry on a plan to send back Bosnian refugees
living in the country, Kinkel said Germany is humane with the
acceptance of refugees and will remain so during repatriations.
</P>
<P>
"No refugees should be forced to wrap up their baggage
overnight," he said.
</P>
<P>
But he also stated that the readiness of German citizens to
take in war refugees also in the future depends on their awareness
that those refugees will eventually return home.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said he has been actively pressing for a speedy
contribution of EU assistance to help the rebuilding of Bosnia,
thus providing conditions for the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that those projects directly related to the
repatriation of refugees, including house building, job creating
and restoration of communal infrastructure, should take priority.
</P>
</TEXT>
