<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Mark Land Day Throughout West Bank, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- At least a dozen of people were
injured today when unarmed Palestinians clashed with Israeli
soldiers during demonstrations or mass rallies held throughout the
West Bank and Gaza Strip to mark the anti-Israeli Land Day.
</P>
<P>
In East Jerusalem, Palestinian residents staged a commercial
strike. Four fire bombs were fired against the Israeli police
headquarters in Ras Al-Amoud, causing some damages in a
neighboring building.
</P>
<P>
Students of Al-Umeh College took to the streets and clashed
with Israeli soldiers in Al-Dahieh by hurling stones.
</P>
<P>
In Shu'fat Refugee Camp and Sur Baher Village, six Palestinians
were wounded by rubber bullets during clashes with Israeli
soldiers. Israeli cars passing through the main road to Giv'at
Zeiv Settlement were stoned by Palestinian youths.
</P>
<P>
In Bethlehem, thousands of Palestinians participated in the
funeral of Abdallah Salah, a Bir Zeit University student and
resident of Beit Sahur, who was killed during clashes with
Israeli soldiers in Ramallah. Senior Palestinian officials
attended the funeral.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Palestinian protesters clashed with Israeli soldiers
guarding Rachel Tomb, a Jewish holy site in Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Some 500 Palestinian youths in Ramallah tried to reach the
Israeli military checkpoint near the Israeli Civil Administration
in Beil El, only to be prevented by Palestinian police. Later in
the afternoon, the Palestinian police banned the demonstrators
from approaching the Israeli military checkpoint in Al-Bireh. The
furious protesters stoned the policemen instead.
</P>
<P>
Clashes also took place in the main Haifa Road in Jenin. Seven
Palestinians were injured by rubber bullets fired by soldiers
while dozens of others suffered gas inhalation.
</P>
<P>
The National Islamic Committee to Confront Settlements
organized a mass rally outside the Jenin Municipality building
under the slogan of "no peace with settlements."
</P>
<P>
Another sit-in was organized by the National Islamic Committee
to Confront Settlements in Wadi Al-Teen, Tulkarm, where
Palestinian land is under threat of being confiscated by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian police in Nablus barred more than 3,000 protesters
from marching toward Joseph Tomb, a Jewish holy site in the
city. The Israeli army deployed tanks near the entrance of the
Palestinian self-rule city.
</P>
<P>
In Hebron, dozens of Hebron University students marched from
the campus to the city center, hurling stones at Israeli
soldiers, who responded with rubber bullets, leaving a number of
students injured.
</P>
<P>
In the Gaza Strip, a number of Palestinian ministers and
Palestinian Council members participated in a massive procession
organized by various factions.
</P>
<P>
Mahmoud Al-Zahar, spokesman of the Islamic Resistance Movement
(Hamas), told reporters that "Israel is pushing our people to an
option of Intifada (uprising)."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Council member Muhammad Abu-Najah condemned the
U.S. for its biased position regarding the peace process, adding
that "The U.S. is no longer interested in the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Some Palestinian youths attempted to approach the Israeli
checkpoint at Netzarim, but were pushed back by Palestinian
police.
</P>
<P>
The Land Day is marked annually in Israel and in the West Bank
and Gaza on the anniversary of an expropriation of Arab-owned land
in northern Israel in 1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
