<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Kesri Accuses Government of Marginalizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress party
President Sitaram Kesri said today that the United Front
government's bid to "marginalize" his party and allow urgent
national issues to take a back seat compelled Congress to withdraw
support to the 14-party minority coalition.
</P>
<P>
In a strongly-worded three-page letter to President Shanker
Dayal Sharma, Kesri, also leader of the Congress Parliamentary
Party, said a "complete collapse" of law and order in the country,
failure to arrest communal and divisive forces and the overall
demoralizing effect on the civil services were among other factors
that led to the decision.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the government of ignoring the principle of collective
responsibility, Kesri said "lack of coordination, direction and
will to govern have created a situation of drift."
</P>
<P>
"In view of the changed situation, the Congress party is
compelled to withdraw its support to the United Front government
with immediate effect," Kesri said.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted at an emergency meeting this afternoon,
the Congress Working Committee (CWC), the party's supreme
decision-making body, welcomed Kesri's decision to withdraw
support to the United Front government led by Prime Minister H.D.
Deve Gowda.
</P>
<P>
Praising Kesri's move to stake a claim to form a new
government, the CWC authorized the party president to take
appropriate steps in this regard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
