<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Two Bamboo Sticks" Effective Way to Help The Poor (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ten years passed, during which time the villagers learned
techniques, step by step, for digging holes, fertilizing, and
trimming the trees, until each household had at least one expert
on apple tree planting.
</P>
<P>
And the County Association of Science and Technology made its
own changes: in addition to distributing to farmers the bamboo
sticks and a nylon rope -- another means of measuring by which
knots are tied at intervals in the rope to indicate the correct
spacing needed between plants -- to setting up a computerized
experience of agricultural experts for local farmers to consult.
</P>
<P>
Yujiaping Village celebrated its first apple harvest in
1994. Since then, financial returns from the apple trees have
become the village's major source of income.
</P>
<P>
New brick houses now are mushrooming throughout the village;
Zhe's six-member family moved from their single-room clay house
into four houses of a dozen rooms that are decorated with
paintings and carvings.
</P>
<P>
The family, which planted 300 apple trees, has also bought a
five-ton truck.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the entire village earned a total of more than
400,000 yuan from selling apples, suggesting an annual per capita
income of over 1,000 yuan, nearly 200 times the 1993 figure.
</P>
<P>
According to the state standard, people with an annual per
capita income of over 530 yuan can be considered over the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
Some 192 million Chinese people escaped poverty in the
1978-1996 period, reducing the proportion of Chinese impoverished
people in the world's total from one fourth to one twentieth.
</P>
<P>
To reach the goal of eliminating poverty by the end of this
century, China has to ensure that some 12 million to 14 million
destitute people have enough to eat each year.
</P>
<P>
To show its determination, the country has decided to increase
state aid-the-poor funding from 10.8 billion to 15.3 billion per
year, starting from 1997.
</P>
<P>
"The largest part of the fund will continue to be allocated to
Yunnan, which has one-tenth of the country's impoverished people,"
says Liu, the department head of the State Council's leading group
for poverty-relief programs.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu, most of the poor people in Yunnan live in
remote mountain areas that are not connected with highways.
</P>
<P>
"Some of them are still engaged in slash-and-burn cultivation,
which means that not only modern farming technology but also
simple ways for spreading technology, such as using the two bamboo
sticks, have to be popularized," he says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0064 </DOCNO>
