<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-American Undersea Cable To Be Built </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- China Telecom today signed a
memorandum of understanding with nine counterparts from the U.S.,
Japan, the Republic of Korea, Hong Kong and Singapore to build an
undersea optical cable to link China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The 26,000 km-cable will cost 1.2 billion US dollars and will
contain more than 241,920 telephone lines and is scheduled to be
completed by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the project is China Telecom, the US AT&AMP;T,
MCI, SBC and Sprint, Japan's NTT and KDD, ROK's KT, and
telecommunications companies from Singapore and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for China Telecom said that the project will be
started sometime this year, and that the project heads also
welcome other overseas telecommunications companies to participate.
</P>
<P>
He said that countries from Asia, North and South America, the
South Pacific regions and Europe can link with the Sino-American
cable through other international cables.
</P>
<P>
China has built undersea cables linking it with Japan and the
Republic of Korea. Construction of the 27,000-km Eurasian ground
optical cable and a Southeast Asian optical cable linking China,
Vietnam, Laos, Thailand, Malaysia and Singapore as well as a
global undersea optical cable will be finished this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
