<HEADLINE> Libyan Airliner Flies Abroad Defying UN Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- A Libyan airliner carried
Saturday 105 Libyan pilgrims, the first batch of Libyans for the
pilgrimage this year, to the Saudi port city of Jeddah, in
defiance of a U.N. air ban, the Libyan news agency (JANA)
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The rest of Libyan pilgrims this year will be transported to
Saudi Arabia during the period from April 10 to 17, the agency
added.
</P>
<P>
The JANA failed to give the time at which the plane landed at
the Jeddah Airport.
</P>
<P>
No word was available so far on how many pilgrims the airline
will fly later and the number of such flights will be made by the
Libyan national airline.
</P>
<P>
Libya has more than once broken the air ban imposed on it in
1992 because of its refusal to extradite two of its citizens being
suspected of having involved in the Pan AM airliner bombing in
Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988, which caused the deaths of 279
passengers.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian National Carrier Egypt Air was supposed to
undertake the job this year, for the third time running, to carry
11,000 Libyan pilgrims to Saudi Arabia as of last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
