<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IWS to Help Upgrade Wool Processing Technology in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The International Wool
Secretariat (IWS) plans to aid China's nationwide program to
improve its wool processing technology in an effort to expand
China's export of wool products, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
Barry White, an official with the IWS, said his organization
expected to help raise interest in Australian wool among wool
processors by upgrading wool processing technology.
</P>
<P>
He said IWS has launched a joint research program with the
Chinese wool processing ventures.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the IWS, more than 1,000 researchers are
studying China's traditional wool-processing techniques and ways
to upgrade the processing technology of Australian wool.
</P>
<P>
The IWS also held discussions with directors from wool mills in
Xi'an, Zhangjiagang, Shanghai and Beijing on the specifications of
the wool processing contracts, technical system improvement,
quality guarantee and environment management, in hopes of helping
these mills obtain big economic returns.
</P>
<P>
White said it is one of the IWS' tasks is to encourage Chinese
ventures to adopt the new wool processing technology, and his
secretariat has decided to provide technical aid for a number of
Chinese factories in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The IWS is also to help wool processing mills collect funds for
purchasing wool.
</P>
<P>
The IWS is a global organization which helps its member states
market its wool products by spreading new technology, developing
new products, transferring technology and analyizing the market.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
