<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Koreans Takes Two Golds in Skating Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- South Koreans Chun Lee-Kyung and
Kim Dong-sung won the women's and men's individual titles
respectively at the world short track speed skating championships
in Nagano, Japan, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yang, from China's Heilongjiang Province, seemed to have a
sure grip on the women's title when she won the 1,000 meters to
snatch a three-point lead.
</P>
<P>
But Chun, 21, stormed home to win the last individual event,
the 3,000 meters, to share the top honor with Yang at 12 points
each.
</P>
<P>
It was the first world individual title for Yang but was the
third consecutive title for Chun.
</P>
<P>
Another South Korean Won Hye was third overall at nine points,
followed by Canadian Isabelle Charest and another Chinese Yang
Yang, who are from Jilin Province.
</P>
<P>
In the 1,000 meters Yang narrowly beat Won and Chun with 0.05
of a second separating the three. In the 3,000 meters the
positions were reversed with Chun leading in Won and Yang with 0.3
seconds between first and third.
</P>
<P>
In the men's competition, Kim beat Canada's three-time world
champion Marc Gagnon to clinch the title, winning the 1,000 meters
and 3,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
Gagnon, who was disqualified for cross tracking in the 1,000
meters final, had to be satisfied with the runner-up spot with
eight points overall, ahead of Japan's Satoru Terao and fellow
Canadian Derrick Campbell with five points.
</P>
<P>
Kim clocked 1:35.18 to beat his teammate Lee Jun-Hwan and
China's Feng Kai in the 1,000 meters, and took the 3,000 meters at
5:14.05, beating Terao and Gagnon to second and thrid.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian women, led by world record holders Charest and
Nathalie Lambert, won the women's 3,000 meters relay in 4:21.23,
with South Korea second, Japan third and Italy fourth.
</P>
<P>
The men's 5,000 meters relay was won by South Korea in 7:00.04,
ahead of Canada, Italy and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
