<HEADLINE> Mixed Reaction to Congress Withdrawal of Support to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Former chief minister and
Congress leader of India's Karnataka State M. Veerappa Moily today
described the party's move to withdraw support to the United Front
(UF) government headed by Deve Gowda as the "right decision."
</P>
<P>
Congress's rank and file was unhappy about the party's support
to the UF government and their wishes had now been fulfilled, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) Atal
Behari Vajpayee said withdrawal of the Congress's support to the
UF government would lead to a mid-term poll.
</P>
<P>
No party was in a position to form an alternative government
and a snap poll was inevitable, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, General Secretary of the Communist Party of India
(CPI) A.B. Bardhan said the Congress would be solely responsible
for sowing seeds of instability in the country by withdrawing
support to the United Front government.
</P>
<P>
The UF stood solidly together and its steering committee would
meet tomorrow to take stock of the situation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister V.P. Singh today described the Congress
decision as a "very short-sighted step" and appealed to leaders of
the Front constituents to unitedly face the challenge.
</P>
<P>
Jagannath Mishra, a senior Congress leader and former
government minister, said the decision to withdraw support to the
UF government was taken in "haste." "A consensus had emerged at
the March 17 meeting of the Congress parliamentary party in Delhi
that a decision on withdrawal of support should not be taken
without getting the nod of the parliamentary party," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
