<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: "Two Bamboo Sticks" Effective Way to Help The Poor (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Zhe Libu, a farmer living on
Xiaoliangshan Mountain in southwest China's Yunnan Province,
clearly recalls when each family in his village received two
bamboo sticks from the county government ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
"The sticks represented the width and depth of a hole to be dug
for planting apple trees," he says. "Most of the people in my
village were illiterate, so it was useless to tell us the
measurements."
</P>
<P>
The two sticks are symbolic of the simplicity that can be found
in China's effective poverty-relief projects. As an official from
the leading group in charge of the work under the State Council
says, "What we lack is not agricultural technology, but a simple
way to spread the technology in backward areas."
</P>
<P>
China has succeeded in reducing its impoverished population
from 125 million to 58 million in the past decade, mostly as a
result of spreading technology to develop planting, breeding and
processing of local agricultural and sideline products,
</P>
<P>
"Planting, breeding and such processing can involve as many
impoverish households as possible, and will help them directly to
shake off poverty," says Liu Fuhe, head of the policy study arm of
the group.
</P>
<P>
Fruit trees are the crop of choice in the remote mountain
areas, where most of the poor people live.
</P>
<P>
A total of one million orchards were built from 1986 to 1996,
including one in Zhe's village in Ninglang County, also called
Xiaoliangshan, which is located 2,800 m above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, none of the 56 families in the village of
Yujiaping wanted to risk giving up planting corn, tomatoes and
buckwheat -- all crops that barely produced a living -- to plant
apple trees.
</P>
<P>
"We didn't believe that we would be able to live a comfortable
life in brick houses if we planted apple trees," Zhe says.
</P>
<P>
For a period of time, several county officials lived with the
villagers, helping them to plant apple trees in the evening and
teaching them to dig holes with the help of two bamboo sticks
during the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
