<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Japan to Safeguard Bilateral Ties: Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that China and Japan, as friendly neighbors sharing similar
traditional culture, should work together to safeguard their
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Li told visiting Japanese Foreign Minister Ikeda Yukihiko
during a meeting that, according to Chinese philosophy, differences
will unavoidably surface during the process of development, and
that handling them properly is what matters most.
</P>
<P>
While sharing much in common, China and Japan still have some
diverging points of view, and statesmen of both countries should
take a farsighted view and lead a healthy and stable bilateral
relationship into the 21st century by proceeding from a regional
and global perceptive and the long-term interest of both
countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He continued that China will see two important events this
year: Hong Kong's return to the motherland and the convening of
the 15th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
China will march straight ahead along the road of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics, a theory initiated by
Deng Xiaoping, he reiterated.
</P>
<P>
As a developing country, China needs a peaceful international
environment, especially a good neighborly environment, to
guarantee its domestic economic construction, and the country will
continue its independent foreign policy of peace, the premier
noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that this year marks the 25th anniversary of the
normalization of diplomatic relations between the two countries,
and also a critical period for improving and developing
Sino-Japanese ties.
</P>
<P>
At present, the overall relationship is good and has brought about
important benefits to both countries, the Chinese leader said.
</P>
<P>
However, Li noted, bilateral ties have also met with
unnecessary interference, and this is not what China wants to see.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the smooth development of bilateral relations, both
China and Japan should stick to the principles set in the
Sino-Japanese Joint Declaration and the Sino-Japan Peace and
Friendship Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda said that over the past 25 years, bilateral ties have
maintained sound development. Japan is willing to further promote
the development of bilateral relations in various sectors with a
view toward the 21st century, and to maintain a more stable and
mature relationship between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
Ikeda extended Prime Minister Hashimoto's invitation to Li for
a visit this year, which Li accepted with thanks. He in return,
reaffirmed his invitation to Hashimoto, saying the details of the
two visits would be discussed by the two foreign ministries.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral economic and trade relations, Li pointed out that
over the past years, economic and trade cooperation between the
two countries have maintained sound development momentum.
</P>
<P>
China's sustainable and healthy economic progress has created
tremendous economic and trade opportunities to countries
throughout the world including Japan, he said, adding there are
broad prospects for further cooperation between the two nations
as their economies are complementary.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, deputy director of
the Foreign Affairs Office of the State Council Lu Congmin, and
Japanese ambassador to China Yoshiyasu Sato were present at
today's meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
