<HEADLINE> Palestinian Information Ministry Statement Marks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) reiterated Palestinian basic rights including the
right of establishing an independent Palestinian state, according
to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
This came in a statement which was issued by the Palestinian
Ministry of Information in the West Bank city of Ramallah on
Saturday night, the eve of the Palestinian Land Day.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one years ago, Israeli Arabs held demonstrations in the Galilee
area, north Israel, to protest Israeli government's confiscation
of Arab land. Many were killed and wounded by Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact of confirming these basic rights of the
Palestinians by the Oslo Accords, the new Israeli right-wing
coalition government started its term in office last year by
resuming the confiscation of the Palestinian lands for building or
expanding Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank, said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Undoubtedly, the statement asserted, "The constant insistence
expressed by the Israeli government to expand Jewish settlements,
will inevitably ruin the peace process in a way which will be
inconsistent with the will of the peoples of the region and with
legitimate international resolutions."
</P>
<P>
The document noted, the struggle is now taking on
"unprecedented tragic dimensions," as the Israeli leadership is
"determined to seize the land and deny the basic rights of the
Palestinian people."
</P>
<P>
The statement called, on the Land Day, on Arabs, Israeli peace
activists and international community to intervene in "the serious
development" so as to rescue the peace process from the "serious
and perilous danger" caused by the extremist policy of the
Netanyahu government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
