<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Oil Export Up 21 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian oil export increased
21.87 percent over the previous year, earning the country 19.5
billion U.S. dollars in the last fiscal year which just ended 10
days ago, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh
in a report carried in the Persian-language daily Jumhuri Islami
here today.
</P>
<P>
Iran, the fourth largest oil producer and the second oil
exporter in the world, is expected to generate 18.5 billion
dollars by exporting 2.5 million barrels per day (bpd) during this
fiscal year starting from March 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Specialists said that the combination of strong prices and
rising production was extremely beneficial to Iran last year.
</P>
<P>
Over the first half of last fiscal year, the Iranian crude
attracted an average price of 17.8 dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
During the fourth quarter of the year, contract prices for
the country's two main kinds of crude, Iranian light and Iranian
heavy, continued to rise, standing at 22.7 dollars per barrel and
21.5 dollars per barrel respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Iran expanded its daily oil production
from 3.6 million bpd to 3.81 million bpd despite the ceiling
limit set by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Japanese oil companies remain the largest foreign lifters
from the Iranian fields, a position they have held since
U.S. companies were forced out by a U.S. trade embargo on Iran.
</P>
<P>
In recent months, the proportion of crude lifted by South
Korean firms has also grown. Ten Japanese companies lifted
562,000 bpd in September, up from the 497,000 bpd in August,
while three South Korean firms lifted 336,000 bpd in September,
compared with the August total of 189,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
The increase of oil export revenue has greatly relieved the
economic crisis in the country, the foreign debt in particular.
</P>
<P>
Iranian authorities said that Iran paid 5.8 billion dollars
foreign debts in 1996. The figure is 3.6 times as much as the
target set in the 1996 budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
