<HEADLINE> More Flowers Enter into Beijingers' Everyday Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Fresh flowers, which in the past
were popular only at festival time, have become a bigger part of
everyday life for people in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The overall sales volume of flowers and plants is expected to
increase by over 30 percent annually from this year through
2000. The sales volume of fresh-cut flowers totaled 96 million
sprays last year.
</P>
<P>
This spring, the capital city's flower market witnessed
unprecedented growth, as the daily sales of fresh-cut flowers
reached about 200,000 sprays, and sometimes up to 500,000. And the
number of flowers bought by individuals for everyday use currently
makes up 30 percent of the city's total sales volume.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from a local flower and plant
association, 256 flower shops and three wholesale markets are now
in operation in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Special retail counters selling fresh flowers have been set up
in big department stores, flower markets and stalls throughout the
city. And some flowers from foreign countries have started to pour
into Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
