<HEADLINE> S. African Tourists Cause Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of South African
tourists are plundering Mozambiques's marine life and turning its
beautiful beaches into filthy wastelands, local daily Sunday
Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Durban-based Environmental Investigation and Protection
Agency, which has an office in Maputo, has launched a probe in
responsesntal to complaints by both Mozambicans and South African
visitors, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The environmentalists said since the end of the Mozambican
civil war in 1992, a flood of tourists has abused the lack of
enforcement of local regulations to overfish the tropical waters.
</P>
<P>
South African holiday makers are also accused of littering;
damaging wildlife at camp sites by dumping raw human sewage
directly into sensitive mangrove swamps or the sea.
</P>
<P>
Durban businessman Peter Foulis, 35, a keen diver and
fisherman who has visited the coastal town of Inhambane, north of
Maputo, for the past three years, is disgusted at the behavior of
his fellow citizens.
</P>
<P>
"I was there in April last year and returned at the end of
December. The change was shocking," Foulis said, warning that "at
this rate of damage, the area will be a desert in two to three
years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
