<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over Half Nigerians Lack Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 30 (Xinhua) -- About 66 percent of the households
in Nigeria have no electricity while only about a quarter of them
use pipe-borne water, according to a latest national survey.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown of the survey, undertaken by the Federal Office of
Statistics (FOS) between 1991 and 1995, shows that 90 percent of
the households in the northern states of Jigawa, Katsina, Kebbi
and Sokoto, as well as Taraba State in the east, have no access
to electricity supply.
</P>
<P>
Lagos State, the commercial center in the southwest, is the
only exception, where only three percent of the households do not
have electricity, the Guardian reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report did not mention the cause of the serious
electricity shortage. But the operation under capacity of the
country's power stations might be one of the factors for the
problem.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now has eight major power stations with a total
installed capacity of 5,961.3 MW. However, the current peak load
of the stations is put at only 2,454 MW due to major breakdown
requiring substantial foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Power and Steel Alhaji Bashir Mohammed Dalhatu
said earlier this week that it will need some 30 million U.S.
dollars for the National Electric Power Authority to rehabilitate
all its power stations.
</P>
<P>
The FOS National Integrated Surveyu of Households also shows
that 49 percent of the population dispose refuse within their
residences, while 38 percent use other places like bush or
dunghill to dispose off their refuse.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, only 11 percent of Nigerian people use their own
bins while only two percent use government bins.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, about 87 percent of Nigerians use
unsatisfactory refuse disposal method which experts say is
responsible for the spread of most communicable diseases in the
country.
</P>
<P>
With 25 percent of the population using pipe-borne water and
only seven percent using bore-hole, the FOS said it is a better
record when compared with electricity usage and waste disposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
