<HEADLINE> S. African Church Leader For Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's biggest
church leader, His Grace Bishop Barnabas Lekganyane, has come out
in favor of the death penalty, said a source here today.
</P>
<P>
Lekganyane, whose Zion Christian Church has an estimated 7
million members in Southern Africa, said the death penalty was a
necessary evil in a society where "criminals brazenly shoot, rape
and maim innocent people".
</P>
<P>
South Africa abolished the death penalty in 1995 as the ruling
African National Congress described it as being unconstitutional
and against the Blacks.
</P>
<P>
Lekganyane said the democratically-elected government should
invest a large portion of the national budget in crime
prevention, and more attention needed to be put into the current
justice system to ensure that criminals would be met by full
strength of law.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke out against the legislation of abortion, saying
education, not the termination of pregnancies was what "our
children need". 
</P>
</TEXT>
