<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Rafsanjani's Visit to S. Arabia Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 29 (Xinhua) -- There has been no confirmation on
the possibility of President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani's official
visit to Saudi Arabia during the hajji season, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Today's Persian dailies Jomhuri Islami and Salam published the
news by the official news agency IRNA's Persian service, which
cited an official source close to the president's office.
</P>
<P>
The report contradicts what had been reported in the London-
based Saudi-owned paper Ash-Sharq-ul-Awsat, which quoted Iranian
Ambassador to Saudi Arabia Mohammad Reza Nouri Friday as saying
that Rafsanjani is expected to make his first official visit to
Saudi Arabia in April to perform the hajji pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the Iranian president pledged his support
to examine all avenues on the improvement of ties with and trip
to the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani's last visit to Saudi Arabia at the start of the
1979 Islamic revolution was a personal visit to perform the
hajji. His wife and daughter had recently visited Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said that Rafsanjani and Saudi Arabian
Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz had discussed the possibility
of a trip by the Iranian president.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that Tehran is eagerly to improve
relations with Saudi Arabia but the latter seems reluctant to
extend invitation to the Iranian president.
</P>
<P>
Iranian hajji pilgrims Saturday vowed to stage demonstrations
in Macca despite a Saudi ban.
</P>
<P>
On March 15, Rafsanjani urged Saudi Arabia to lift the ban on
anti-U.S. and anti-Israel rally during a Muslim pilgrimage in
Mecca next month.
</P>
<P>
He said "Saudi officials in charge of the pilgrims' affairs
would understand the stands of the Islamic Republic of Iran
toward the Muslim world and would prepare the ground for Hajji
rituals to be held as recommended by the Holy Koran."
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani said cooperation between Iran and Saudi Arabia will
serve to revive the great power of Islam and put it at the
disposal of Muslim nations.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the statement by the 64-year-old
Iranian president served as an official response to the customary
warning issued by the Saudi authorities that political activities
will not be tolerated during the Hajji, which is due to take place
in April this year.
</P>
<P>
Such demonstrations have previously led to tense situation and
even bloody confrontations with the Saudi security forces. In
1987, more than 400 people were killed in clashes between Iranian
demonstrators and Saudi forces. The two countries broke off
relations from 1988 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi authorities kept a close watch on Iranian pilgrims
in past years, trying to prevent them from holding any rallies in
public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
