<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Countries to Take Firm Stance on Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Arab countries are expected to
take a firm stance to force Israel to back off from building a
Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem during a meeting of Arab
League's foreign ministers, which opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and 18 foreign ministers from
the Arab League member states attended the meeting, which will
last for two days.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League Council meeting, though a routine gathering,
is aimed at formulating a common Arab response to Israel's
settlement construction in East Jerusalem, which the Arabs said
has severely challenged the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries have time and again appealed to the U.S. to
pressure Israel into abiding by relevant U.N. resolutions, but
the U.S. has failed to make it comply.
</P>
<P>
The limelight will be on the Israeli settlement practices in
East Jerusalem and other occupied Arab lands, an issue that has
sparked wide-spread Palestinian rioting and put the peace process
in jeopardy since late last month.
</P>
<P>
Also on agenda are the support of the Palestinian Intifada
(uprisings) against Israel, Palestinian refugees and other
developments on Palestinian lands. The league's Secretary
General, Esmat Abdel Meguid, has said earlier that Arab foreign
ministers will take up the support of Intifada as "a major prop
against the Israeli arrogance."
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministers are expected to discuss altogether
45 hot topics, including the Arab-Israeli conflicts, the peace
process and other issues pertaining to the joint Arab action
during their two-day meeting at the league's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Several draft resolutions are expected to be reviewed. One of
the draft resolutions calls for freezing normalization procedures
with Israel and maintaining economic boycott against it until
just and comprehensive peace agreements on all tracks were
concluded.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian talks have broken down as Israel last
week sent bulldozers to Jabal Abu Ghneim, the site of a planned
6,500-unit Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem, where
Palestinians hope to establish their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized East Jerusalem in the 1967 war and wants the
entire city to remain undivided under Israeli
sovereignty. Clashes between Palestinian stone-throwers and
Israeli soldiers plagued the West Bank and Gaza ever since,
including a suicide bombing attack that killed four people in a
Tel Aviv cafe last week.
</P>
<P>
Some Arab countries, such as Oman and Qatar, have suspended
their relations with Israel and while others like Egypt, Israel's
biggest Arab partner, has sent a similar signal, if it fails to
backtrack on the controversial housing decision.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the Arab and Muslim world, at a flurry of
meetings for the past few days, have come up with several
resolutions calling on Arab and Muslim countries to review their
ties with Israel, a move aimed to pressure the Jewish state to
stop building the settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak said Saturday that Israel
would be playing with fire if it proceeds with the Jewish
building project in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"Tensions and violence will not cease until the construction
stops... There is no other solution," he warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
