<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Leaders Call for Closing Ranks Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Arab leaders, intensive on a
campaign to close ranks, have stressed the exigency of overcoming
differences among themselves and standing up against Israel's
challenge to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
President of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Yasser
Arafat said the current stage is "the most delicate phase of the
peace process," as Israel has made a further move to change the
demographic and geographical features of East Jerusalem by
building a Jewish neighborhood there.
</P>
<P>
This came in a written speech by Arafat late Saturday before
the inaugural session of a seminar here under the title of "the
Arab visualization of peace."
</P>
<P>
In his speech, read out on his behalf, the Palestinian leader
said the real meaning of peace and Arab participation in the peace
process have become dubious as the Israeli buildings in East Jerusalem
have aggravated the apprehensions of the Palestinians far and wide.
</P>
<P>
"We have sustained continued sufferings since the very
beginning of the peace process in order to safeguard the
foundations of peace," he complained.
</P>
<P>
Arab League chief Esmat Abdul-Meguid, in his speech, said the
peace process is going through one of its most difficult stages
owing to the Israeli intransigence and attempts to circumvent
peace commitments and agreements as well as its insistence on
building Jewish settlements on Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
He called upon Israeli leaders to realize that no peace can be
attained through imposing a state of fait accompli and urged the
U.S. to stop "supporting Israel."
</P>
<P>
In his speech that was read out on his behalf, Jordanian Crown
Prince Hassan Ibn Talal said Arab countries should set aside their
differences emanating from "the discrepancy of talks on the
various peace tracks with Israel" since the Camp David agreement
signed by Egypt and Israel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Prince Hassan underscored the importance of reviewing causes
behind the "weakness of the Arab order" and called for
consolidating Arab relations with western, Asian and African
countries.
</P>
<P>
"We have to prove to the world that no peace can be established
without Israel's abidance by all relevant international
resolutions," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, in his speech, accused
Israel of neglecting the rights of the Palestinians and Arabs at
large to guarantee the Israeli security. He condemned the Israeli
policy that he described as based on "maltreatment and holding the
Arabs solely responsible for the current peace stalement."
</P>
<P>
The Arab foreign ministers are meeting here at the Arab League
headquarters today as part of their latest efforts to map out a
common strategy to cope with Israel's housing plan in East
Jerusalem, which has sparked Palestinian rioting and put the
Middle East peace process in jeopardy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
