<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 08:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: Unity Government Not Under </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu has dismissed speculations that he is
currently preoccupied with the idea of forming a national unity
government in order to tide over the difficulties in the peace
process, the state-run Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
A national unity government "is not a practical option right
now," said Netanyahu while addressing a gathering of Likud
activists in Tel Aviv Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
He did not, however, rule out the formation of a national
unity government in the future.
</P>
<P>
The rightwing premier disclosed that he had invited the major
opposition Labor Party to join his government several times
since the election. "I told them they could enter the government
on the basis of the existing coalition guidelines. Labor (Party)
was the side that declined (the offer)," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speculations have been rife about the idea of forming a
national unity government, in view of the fact that Netanyahu is
facing challenges not only from the left parties but also from his
coalition partners over the deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
Shimon Peres, Labor Party Chairman and former prime minister, is
believed to be interested in joining a projected unity
government in an effort to save the peace march from further
deteriorating.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was reported to
have privately advised Israel to form a unity government so as
to extricate itself from the current crisis. But the Clinton
Administration has officially stated that it is simply an
internal affair of Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
