<HEADLINE> Italy Welcomes U.N. Approval for Troop Dispatch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini said today that Italy welcomed the U.N. Security Council's
approval for the dispatch of a multinational force to Albania for
at least three months to protect aid delivery and help recover
peace there.
</P>
<P>
The vote represented "the definitive endorsement of the
international community for the Italian and European commitment to
pacification in Albania," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council approved a proposal presented by the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) that a
military force should be sent to Albania to guard relief supplies
and facilitate the work of the OSCE and European Union in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Dini said the urgency of restoring the democratic process and
public order in Albania needs create conditions which would help
stem the flow of refugees to Italy across the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
The approval would also reduce tragic accidents. Last night in
the Ottanto channel at least four Albanians died after their boat
was capsized and sank after a collision with an Italian naval
vessel.
</P>
<P>
More than 13,000 Albanians have crossed the Adriatic to Italy
since the crisis broke out in Albania earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The number of the multinational force is expected to be about
2,500 from Spain, Portugal, France, Greece and Austria in the
initial phase. Its main tasks would be to secure the ports and
airport in the small European country to guarantee the
humanitarian aid to transport there safely.
</P>
<P>
Italian troops have been waiting in the Brindisi area on a
24-hour alert for orders to cross to Albania since last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
