<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Grant Autonomy to Nationalized Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government is
considering a proposal to give total autonomy to four
profit-making nationalized banks regarding fixation of pay scales
and determination of service conditions, a Finance Ministry
official said here today.
</P>
<P>
If the proposal is implemented, then the banks will be able to
determine their own pay scales and act beyond the scope of
bipartite settlements at the industry level.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, these banks will also be at liberty to have their own
service conditions for the staff.
</P>
<P>
At present, the pay scales and the service conditions of the
bank staff are determined through the bipartite settlements.
</P>
<P>
The four nationalized banks, selected by the Finance Ministry
for being offered the autonomy, are the State Bank of India, the
Union Bank of India, the Corporation Bank and the Oriental Bank of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to grant total autonomy is on the grounds that
these banks have shown a net profit in the last three consecutive
years; Their amount of non-performing assets was below 10 percent;
And they have been able to maintain a capital adequacy ratio
higher than the stipulated level of eight percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
