<HEADLINE> Prodi Says Shipwreck Makes Albanian Mission Urgent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
said today that the sinking of an Albanian refugee boat had made
an international mission to help Albania more urgent.
</P>
<P>
An Albanian naval patrol boat carrying refugees went down on
Friday night after colliding with an Italian naval vessel
patrolling the Adriatic to try to stem the flow of Albanians to
southern Italy.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said the sinking of the ship, which killed at least four,
"demonstrates that the international operation to help Albania
must start as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
An Italy-led international force to guard aid deliveries have
been assembled near the southern port city of Brindisi for several
days, waiting for an order from the Italian Defense Ministry to
move to Albania.
</P>
<P>
The mission was authorized by the U.N. Security Council late on
Friday to help Albania recover from violence and anarchy.
</P>
<P>
More than 13,000 Albanians have reached Italy in the past two
weeks on a flotilla of ancient boats after rebels in the south
took control of towns in an armed insurrection.
</P>
<P>
The sinking was the first incident involving fatalities since
the exodus began on March 13.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said a navy operation to patrol
the southern Adriatic and stem a tide of refugees would continue
because it had Albanian government approval.
</P>
<P>
"That does not mean that we will stop welcoming people who need
help, aid or assistance, those who are among the weakest, such as
children, old people and women, who will be welcomed in Italy as
they have been so far," Dini said.
</P>
<P>
He added:" This (the sinking) was an accident which nobody
wanted, but it will have no negative repercussions on relations
between the Italian and Albanian authorities." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
