<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile Considers Separate Proposals on Trade Bloc in America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Chile said today it hopes to
make separate proposals on the proposed Free Trade Area of the
Americas (ALCA) at the Second Summit of the Americas, scheduled
for March next year in the Chilean capital of Santiago.
</P>
<P>
Juan Martabit, director of the Americas Section of the Chilean
Foreign Ministry, said Chile, as the host country of the
hemispheric gathering, wants to present an individual document on
the negotiation mechanisms and themes of the ALCA, over which the
United States and Brazil have different views.
</P>
<P>
"There is an opportunity to present a counterproposal in which
we are working, through coordination with other countries," said
Martabit.
</P>
<P>
The ALCA was proposed by 34 American countries at the First
Summit of the Americas held in December 1994 in Miami, the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The pan-Ameircan trade bloc, which would bring together 750
million people in diverse countries as Haiti and the U.S., was
supposed to be established by 2005 as set by the Miami summit, but
participating countries have remained far divided over its
creation.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government has pledged to push forward the
establishment of the trade bloc but polls show Americans in the
U.S. oppose trade agreements that would send U.S. jobs abroad.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, which is a member of Mercosur consisting of Argentina,
Uruguay and Paraguay, insists that Mercosur should be
strenghthened first as a counterweight of the North American Free
Trade Area, which groups the U.S., Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Martabit said a major task of the Second Summit of the Americas
was to coordinate the stances on the ALCA.
</P>
<P>
He said part of the differences had been discussed at the ALCA
trade ministers' meeting in February in Recife, Brazil.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Second Summit of the Americas will also
discuss agreements to be signed at the Third Conference of Trade
Ministers of the ALCA, scheduled for May in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Martabit announced today the creation of working teams for the
Second Summit of the Americas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's LTTE Seeks 3rd-Party Mediation for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 30 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan rebel group, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE), has insisted on a
third-party mediation for resuming talks with the government,
according to Tamil sources here today.
</P>
<P>
However, The LTTE gave two preconditions for talks to end the
ethnic conflict, the sources quoted a LTTE's representative as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The first one is that government troops must withdraw from
current positions in the North and return to their original bases
held before the military operation in which the Jaffna peninsula
was recaptured by the troops in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
The second is that the government must accept the LTTE as the
sole representative of the Tamil people.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE representative did not indicate any country or
organization which would be acceptable as a third-party mediator.
</P>
<P>
However, the government said earlier the LTTE should lay down
arms and a specific time frame should be fixed for any
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels have been fighting for a separate state in the
North and East of Sri Lanka since 1983. More than 55,000 people
have been reportedly killed in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after coming to power in 1994, The People's Alliance
government opened talks with the LTTE, but in April 1995 the
rebels abruptly pulled out to resume their protracted campaign for
an independent homeland in the island country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
