youths in a racially motivated attack, began to recover.
</P>
<P>
Lenard Clark, was dressed up, helped out of bed, and looked at
photographs of his family today, the United Press International
reported.
</P>
<P>
The 13-year-old boy was beaten unconscious on March 21 while
bicycling with two friends in Armour Square Park near the
white-predominated enclave of Bridgeport on the South Side.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the Rehabilitation Institute of Chicago said Clark
would face months, possibly years, of recovery as he emerged from
a coma.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said he won't remember the savage beating, which
U.S. President Bill Clinton called "a senseless assault" in his
regular Saturday radio address, and will not be able to testify
against the teens charged with attempted murder and hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
All three defendants are now in custody. 
