<HEADLINE> Glass Buildings Reflect Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Beijing shines with blue-mirrored
buildings that reflect a fortune for glass manufacturers and a
hazard for residents.
</P>
<P>
Since the first glass high-rise -- the Great Wall Sheraton
Hotel -- was erected in Beijing in 1985, similar buildings have
been blossoming in the capital, Shanghai, Shenzhen, Guangzhou, and
other major cities, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
China builds four million to five million square meters of
glass walls a year. They are worth about 4.5 billion yuan (542
million US dollars). China has about 15 million square meters of
glass buildings.
</P>
<P>
The glass walls reflect the sun, cause temperatures to rise in
the neighborhood and blind passers-by, which might cause danger
for drivers.
</P>
<P>
Concerns about such "light pollution" are increasing, said Guo
Xiulan, a State Environmental Protection Agency official.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Environmental Protection Bureau received similar
complaints, and Shanghai media have received more than 100 letters
of complaint, according to a report in People's Daily last week.
</P>
<P>
The complaints have led to limits on new glass buildings.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Beijing urban planning committee vetoed a plan to
install glass walls for a complex in the eastern part of the
city. It demanded the developers not use blue glass to avoid
light pollution.
</P>
<P>
The committee has vetoed about 30 construction plans for
similar reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
