<HEADLINE> Two HK Heroin Traffickers Sentenced to Death in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Two heroin traffickers from Hong
Kong were sentenced to death in Ho Chi Minh City Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two Hong Kong residents holding British passports,
34-years-old Sun Chi-Kin and 24-years-old Chan Chun-Hung Sam My
were arrested in March last year after customs officers found 18.1
kilograms of heroin hidden in their two suitcases. They arrived at
Ho Chi Minh City's international airport from Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
A court official was quoted by today's Vietnam News as saying
that the two men who carried false Portugese passports issued in
Macao were transiting in Ho Chi Minh City in order to transport
the drugs to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Court officials said the trial lasted one day and the two men
have 15 days to appeal.
</P>
<P>
Possession or transporting more than one kilogram of heroin is
punishable by death in Vietnam. Up to now four foreigners have
previously received death sentences for drug-related crimes in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Vietnam uncovered more than 3,800 cases of drug
trafficking and arrested 6,650 people for drug-related offences.
</P>
<P>
However, official sources here said drug trafficking and abuse
in Vietnam is still on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Most of those susceptible to drug addiction are young
people. The arrest of four heroin dealers and 94 young drug users
earlier this month in Ho Chi Minh City shocked the country.
</P>
<P>
A report made by the anti-narcotics program of the national
committee for ethnic minorities and the highlands said that there
are about 140,000 drug addicts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Government continues to crack down on drugs. An
all-out propaganda campaign was waged by the Communist Youth
League, the Women's Union and the Environment Bureau beginning on
March 13 in Ho Chi Minh City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
