<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Confident in RMB business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Foreign banks licensed to deal in
renminbi claim full confidence in their new business and China's
financial reforms, reported today's Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The move shows China's financial sector is more open and
improving, said Johnson Cheng, deputy general manager of the
International Bank of Paris and Shanghai (IBPS).
</P>
<P>
The bank, a joint venture between Banque National de Paris and
Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, is the first Sino-foreign
bank to receive the yuan license.
</P>
<P>
Cheng said the bank would be able to offer more banking
services to its multinational clients and potential investors in
China.
</P>
<P>
The bank plans to kick off its new business in June after it
moves to an office in Pudong.
</P>
<P>
Some foreign banks said restrictions exist for the foreign
banks when handling yuan deposits and loans. Their clients must
be either foreign-funded firms or foreign individuals.
</P>
<P>
Eddie Wang, chief executive officer for the Hongkong and
Shanghai Banking Co Ltd (HSBC) in China, said the restrictions
were understandable at this stage because the success of China's
previous reforms has been achieved step by step.
</P>
<P>
HSBC initiated local currency business last Wednesday with the
Industrial Bank of Japan.
</P>
<P>
A senior official from Daiichi Kangyo Bank echoed Wang's view.
He said he was confident in the new business.
</P>
<P>
"We don't think there is any problem," he said. "It largely
depends on our service to attract clients."
</P>
<P>
Daiichi Kangyo Bank is expected to start renminbi business in
mid April. Other licensed to deal in renminbi are Citibank, the
Industrial Bank of Japan, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd,
Standard Chartered Bank and Sanwa Bank, the paper said. 
</P>
