<HEADLINE> Treasures Found on Sunken Spanish Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, March 29 (Xinhua) -- A 40-kilogram silver bar, ceramics
fragments and some 150 pieces of ancient silver coins were found
when a team of divers were searching for treasures in a Spanish
ship sunken in Ecuadoran waters more than 300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Minting dates and the image of Felipe IV, then king of Spain,
are still recognizable on the coins, divers from the Sudamerica
Discoveries company said.
</P>
<P>
The findings are only part of between 3.7 billion and 7.5
billion dollars of treasures that went down with the Spanish ship
in 1654, said company president German Moro.
</P>
<P>
The rescue of the Spanish ship kicked off on March 19, when two
U.S. divers hired by the company made the first immersion in the
sea off the Cacerio Real town, Guayas province.
</P>
<P>
The ship was called "Jesus Maria de la Limpia Concepcion de
Nuestra Senora, la Capitana Real".  
</P>
