<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Make Higher Demand for Accounting Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- the Chinese commercial banking
sector, which is moving to become market-oriented, will provide
more opportunities for accounting firms, the Business Weekly of
China Daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The banks want to prevent risks and intend to establish a good
business image, so they would need accounting firms to check
their books and write financial reports more frequently, said Fu
Yi, an official with the Chinese Institute of the Certified Public
Accountants.
</P>
<P>
"It's an international practice that commercial banks employ
CPAs," he said. "Accounting firms have business opportunities in
every aspect of a bank's management."
</P>
<P>
In the planned-economy era, Chinese banks were tools for the
government to allocate funds to projects and used simple methods
to record their business activities.
</P>
<P>
The country's financial reforms launched in the 1980s are
commercializing most domestic banks.
</P>
<P>
To standardize operation, the banks have begun to strengthen
their international accounting while enlisting public auditing
institutions to accurately evaluate the quality of their assets.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with international practices, balance sheets
audited by public accounting firms gradually will be accepted as
the only language for commercial banks to communicate with
financial regulators and the public, Fu said.
</P>
<P>
Competition among the accounting firms for clients in the
banking sector is inevitable, Fu said.
</P>
<P>
This year, the China Minsheng Banking Co, the country's newest
and only non-state bank, hired international accounting firm Price
Waterhouse to write its 1996 annual report.
</P>
<P>
In competing for Chinese banking clients, international CPAs,
with more expertise and experiences, could win part of the market,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Challenges from foreign firms will drive domestic CPAs to merge
and become strong enough to conduct bank auditing, which is one
of the most demanding jobs of an accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
However, domestic CPAs will have some advantages in the
competition, especially in serving banks transforming from their
former roles to commercial banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Prospecting Resource Reserves in International Seabed (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Desheng, a well-known Chinese petro-geologist, warned that
China's current proven oil reserves dry up within 20 years' time,
and the proven reserves of copper and manganese ores only account
for one fifth of the estimated volume.
</P>
<P>
Observers predict that by 2020, about 40 percent of China's oil
demands will be met by imports.
</P>
<P>
Plenty of oil, gas, biological resources, and polymetallic
nodules of economic value are hidden in the world's vast area of
seabed, including about 70 billion tons of polymetallic resources
which are of high industrial exploration value.
</P>
<P>
With the approval of the United Nations, China was given the
right to explore resources in 150,000-sq-km sea areas in
northeastern Pacific Ocean in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, China has sent four ships and rigs,
with some 400 workers, to carry out prospecting in several
hundreds of positions in the marine region.
</P>
<P>
Through prospecting experiments, experts have found
huge amount of dry nodules and manganese, copper, nickel and
cobalt in the marine mining areas reserved for China, which are
liable to commercial exploitation for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that China is expected to concentrate development
within 75,000 sq km seabed areas through further operations and
will make preparations for formal commercial exploitation as early
as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England Nips Mexico in Soccer Friendly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- England beat Mexico 2-0 in a
Wembley soccer friendly on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Teddy Sheringham put the home side ahead from the spot in the
18th minute after defender Pavel Pardo was adjudged to have
tripped England captain Paul Ince in the box.
</P>
<P>
Bobbie Fowler sealed England's victory after the break with a
close range header after Mexico keeper Aldolfo Rios had parried an
initial header from Ian Wright.
</P>
<P>
It was Fowler's first goal for his country in his sixth
appearance. 
</P>
