<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Prospecting Resource Reserves in International Seabed (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 30 (Xinhua) -- Two scientific prospecting
vessels flying the Chinese national flag will soon leave for the
northeastern Pacific Ocean to conduct prospecting.
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at finding strategic resource reserves for
China in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Jin Jiancai, Secretary-General of China Ocean Mineral Resources
Research and Development Association, said that as part of the
four scheduled large-scale ocean prospecting events this century,
the two vessels will spend half a year on prospecting over 100,000
sq km sea areas with the aid of advanced equipment and robots
capable of working at 6,000 m below the sea surface.
</P>
<P>
The mission will also be responsible for surveying distribution
of mineral resources and mining environment at the 5,000-m-deep
seabed, making preparations for developing the un-tapped marine
resources on a large-scale in the next century and hoping to wage
commercial exploitation in 2010.
</P>
<P>
Prospecting in the international seabed, which started in the
late 1950s, has been considered by the scientific community as the
"aerospace technology of the seabed" as such activities require
the use of a large number of sophisticated technologies.
</P>
<P>
However, the captivating commercial prospects in this field
have attracted a group of scientists from western countries and
the former Soviet Union, and some international consortia.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten years, some countries have launched
international events termed as "exploiting the common property of
mankind" in accordance with "United Nations Convention on the Law
of the Sea".
</P>
<P>
Up to now, scientists have verified oil and gas reserves in 50
percent of the seabed area of the earth, which is believed to
double the proven oil and gas reserves on land, and have also
discovered a large amount of minerals which might be able to be
used as substitute energy in the 21st century, as well as
biological resources capable of being used for human medical and
health care purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Draws Portugal in World Cup Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland held Portugal to
a 0-0 draw in a World Cup European Group Nine qualifier in Belfast
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bryan Hamilton's team, needing a win to enhance their slim
hopes of reaching next year's finals in France, played with their
usual gusto and spirit, but could not break down the visitors'
defence.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, who also needed to win to stretch their lead over
Ukraine and Germany, rarely looked settled under the home side's
pressure.
</P>
<P>
The Irish could have led as early as the fifth minute when
Keith Gillespie fed captain Iain Dowie down the right and his
cross looked perfect for the unmarked James Quinn only for the
youngster to scuff his shot into the arms of Portugal keeper Vitor
Baia from close range.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, despite going into the game with a record of just
five goals in seven matches since Euro 96, soon showed their
attacking flair and Joao Pinto squandered a great chance when he
shot wide from 16 yards.
</P>
<P>
The contest threatened to boil over at times and Quinn and
Portugal's Fernando Couto were booked by Italian referee Graziano
Cesari in the 59th minute for a touchline flare-up.
</P>
<P>
Home keeper Tommy Wright was kept more and more busy as the
match wore on, tipping over a thundering volley from Barcelona
star Figo and later racing forward to block Joao Pinto with the
Irish defence ball-watching.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland have now gathered only five points from four
home qualifiers and only European champions Germany have still to
visit Belfast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
