<HEADLINE> Villeneuve Wins Pole Position in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Jacques Villeneuve took
pole position for Sunday's Brazilian Grand Prix after winning the
qualifying in Sao Paulo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old Williams driver went fastest on his opening run
after only eight minutes of the one-hour session and stayed as
the quickest throughout.
</P>
<P>
It was Villeneuve's second pole this season and the fifth of
his career.
</P>
<P>
His fastest lap of one minute 16.004 seconds left him half a
second clear of his nearest rival, double world champion Michael
Schumacher of Germany in a Ferrari.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Gerhard Berger in a Benetton was third-quickest ahead
of Finland's Mika Hakkinen in a McLaren. Frenchman Olivier Panis,
in a Prost, was fifth and Jean Alesi, also of France, sixth in the
second Benetton.  
</P>
