<HEADLINE> 50,000 Demonstrate Against National Front in French City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- At least 50,000 people staged in
Strasbourg today a gigantic demonstration with what was described
by reports as "unprecedented mobilization" to protest against the
extreme-right National Front (FN) party of Jean-Marie Le Pen.
</P>
<P>
All the French leftwing parties, trade unions, and cultural
organizations joined in the demonstration, which took place also
today when 2,200 FN delegates began a three-day national congress
in the eastern French city.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators included people from all parts of France as
well as their supporters from Germany, Switzerland and Britain.
Some demonstrators wore the grey and white strip garments of Nazi
death camps to show their indignation at the fascist ideas of Le
Pen, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
First Secretary of the French Socialist Party Lionel Jospin,
National Secretary of the French Communist Party Robert Hue, and
Socialist Mayor of Strasbourg Catherine Trautmann took part in the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Also among the demonstrators were citizens of the four southern
French cities which are under the administrative control of the FN
-- Toulon, Orange, Marignane and Vitrolles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, FN President Le Pen defied the protest and claimed
that the FN would win 40 percent of the votes in the elections in
future.
</P>
<P>
The FN is trying to take advantage of the social problems of
the country, such as its high unemployment rate, to win supporters
for their extreme-right political ideas and seek to enter the
French parliament in the 1998 legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
During the congress, the FN is expected to re-elect Le Pen as
its president and to recommend a "constitutional reform" to stress
"national preference" of France by putting "the supremacy of the
national laws and constitution above international and European
laws." 
</P>
</TEXT>
