<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls for Racial Harmony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 29 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton,
in his weekly radio address today, called racism "America's
constant curse" in the pursuit of its ideals.
</P>
<P>
Clinton cited the most recent example in Chicago to show that
there is more work to be done to eliminate racism. In Chicago only
days ago, a 13-year-old African-American teen was severely beaten
by three white youths.
</P>
<P>
Lenard Clark suffered severe head injuries but doctors say he
is slowly coming out of a coma at Children's Memorial Hospital in
Chicago, according to media reports.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "This kind of savage, senseless assault, driven
by nothing but hate, strikes at the very heart of America's ideals
and threatens the promise of our future."
</P>
<P>
"We must stand together as a nation against all crimes of hate
and say they are wrong," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"We must condemn hate crimes whenever they happen. We must
commit ourselves to prevent them from happening again. And we must
sow the seeds of harmony and respect among our people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the three suspects in the attack, aged
respectively 19, 18 and 17, are charged with attempted murder and
committing a hate crime and are free on bond.
</P>
<P>
Clark and two friends were bicycling home from playing
basketball Friday when they were attacked near Armor Square Park
on the edge of the predominately white ethnic neighborhood of
Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
Clark lives in the all-black Stateway Gardens public housing
development a few blocks away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
