<HEADLINE> Muslim Official Slams Serb-Yugoslav Customs Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, March 29 (Xinhua) -- A senior Bosnian Muslim official
warned today that a customs agreement between Serbs and Yugoslavia
would block the progress of the central government work in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here, the Serb republic, one of
the two entities of Bosnia, reached an agreement Friday with
Yugoslavia on unitary customs and tariffs which would go into
effect on June 10.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the news on BiH TV, Bosnian Foreign Trade
Minister Hasan Muratovic, a Muslim, said, "If this is true, it
will completely block the process of passing laws of the quick
start package."
</P>
<P>
The referred package consists of bills which should be passed
before the start of an international conference on assistance to
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The conference has already been postponed several times because
Bosnian Serbs and Muslims cannot settle their differences on such
economic issues as unitary currency, customs and budget.
</P>
<P>
Muratovic accused Serbs of delaying the adoption of customs
laws in the joint body of Council of Ministers, while unilaterally
reaching such agreement with Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
