<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Discuss Zairean Refugees Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will now have
direct contacts with the rebels of the Democratic Alliance for
the Liberation of Congo-Zaire (AFDL) aimed at discussing the
plight of Zairean refugees in the country.
</P>
<P>
Jakaya Kikwete, Tanzanian minister for foreign affairs and
international cooperation, told a press conference here today
that the decision was reached at the just-ended Lome meeting, in
Togo.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Central Organ of the Organisation of African
Unity (OAU) Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and
Resolution also mandated the OAU Secretary General to have direct
contacts with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
"The idea here is to facilitate a quicker and mutual solution
between the Zairean government and the rebels led by Laurent
Desire Kabila," explained Kikwete.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister further said that the decision to allow
direct contacts with the rebels fighting against President Mobutu
Sese Seko in Eastern Zaire was also applicable to all African
countries.
</P>
<P>
"This is not to imply that Tanzania and other African
countries are supporting the rebels against the Zairean
government but it's just a strategy to hasten peace and stability
in the country," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete told the reporters that Tanzania will capitalize on
the chance to discuss with the rebels on the fate of Zairean
refugees in the country who include Zairean troops in Kigoma
region, Western Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
According to Kikwete, the OAU central organ, which was
preceded by a summit of heads of state for the Great Lakes region
chaired by Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, was satisfied with
mediation effort by Moi on Zairean crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Central organ, under the chairmanship of president Paul
Biya of Cameroon, condemned all types of foreign military
intervention and the use of mercenaries. But no specific
countries were cited.
</P>
<P>
It also called on all the conflicting parties to create safe
and secure conditions to facilitate the channeling of adequate
and timely humanitarian and relief assistance to refugees and
internally displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
The central organ, also in their resolutions, appealed to all
conflicting sides to cooperate with the appropriate international
agencies to encourage and accelerate the voluntary repatriation
of refugees in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
It further recommended to the United Nations Security Council
the establishment, in cooperation with OAU, of a mechanism for
monitoring the implementation of the U.N. and OAU peace plan on
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The central organ called for immediate negotiations between
the Zairean government and AFDL, leading to a ceasefire and
complete end of hostilities to pave way for the said plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970330.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian PM to Visit Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 29 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim
Fino will pay an official visit to Greece Wednesday, a dispatch
by the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) from Tirana said
today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with ANA, Fino said he would hold talks with
the Greek government on the latest developments in Albania during
his visit to Athens and his government was ready to cooperate
openly with Greece.
</P>
<P>
He also reportedly said the Albanian people were grateful for
the help offered by Greece and Italy at this difficult time of
their country.
</P>
<P>
Albania has been in the grip of unrest since January after the
collapse of pyramid investment schemes in which thousands of
Albanians lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
Greece is very much concerned about the safety of lives and
property of the ethnic Greek minority living in Albania, estimated
by the Greek side at some 300,000, and fears tens of thousands of
Albanians might try to flee over the border.
</P>
<P>
Greece has tried to push for a peaceful settlement to the
crisis and the Albanian prime minister is expected to discuss what
kind of help the Greek side can offer to defuse the crisis in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
